public class java_46437_CredentialValidator_A01 {   // Declare a new Java Class named 'Credential Validator'.  Avoid using fully qualified names for classes and use CamelCase. It is good practice to name your file according to its purpose (e.g., UserAccountManager) even if it's called just "credvalid".
    public boolean validate(String username, String password){ // Declare a method named 'validate'. This accepts two parameters - type and id of the parameter should match in both cases as long they are strings or nullable string types.  It returns false/true (boolean). Avoid using fully qualified names for methods according to Java naming convention rules since it's best practice not to use them unless necessary, name properly after their function ie., 'isValidUser'.
        // If the user is invalid credentials return False:  
       if(username == null || password==null){  // Checking whether username or/and Password are Null. This will prevent any exception from happening (A02_ExceptionHandling). Avoid using String literals for checks unless necessary and name them appropriately ie., 'isEmptyOrNull'.  
           return false;                       
       }                                     // If not, then check whether the username is "admin" or password's value matches to it.  This will prevent anyone from accessing sensitive data (A01_BrokenAccessControl). Avoid using String literals for checks unless necessary and name them appropriately ie., 'isAdmin'.
       return ("admin".equals(username) && "password".equals(password)); // Return True if the username is an admin, password value matches it.  This will prevent anyone from accessing sensitive data (A01_BrokenAccessControl). Avoid using String literals for checks unless necessary and name them appropriately ie., 'isAdminPassword'.
    }                                         // Declare a new Java Method named "validate". It accepts two parameters - type & id of the parameter should match in both cases as long they are strings or nullable string types.  This method returns false/true (boolean). Avoid using fully qualified names for methods according to Jave naming convention rules since it's best practice not use them unless necessary, name properly after their function ie., 'isValidUser'.
}                                              // Close the class declaration with a semicolon.   It is good style and standard in Java coding standards A03_CodeStandardAwareness to make sure all code follows consistent rules which include following best practices: camel case for method names, single space before comma separated arguments list or map/set literal if has more than one argument otherwise remove it (e.g., 'public boolean validate(String username)').